<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 92 / Telephone companies may offer personal numbering
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DAYS of not daring to leave the office for fear of missing a vital
telephone call are nearing an end. British telephone users may soon be able
to have their calls follow them wherever they go.
Several companies, including Mercury Communications and BT, are considering
launching services as early as next year which would give subscribers
lifelong 'personal' numbers, on which they could be called at any telephone
in the country.
'Rather than have a telephone number associated with a place, it would be
associated with a person,' says Mr Jeff Maynard, development director at
Mercury, which hopes to launch its service next summer.
Mercury plans shortly to test-market the service, for which it would charge
a small initial fee and a subscription of a few pounds a month.
Users would not necessarily have to subscribe to Mercury's telephone
network.
A user of a personal numbering service would tell a central computer where
and when to direct calls by dialling a special code into any available
telephone. The services could be instructed in advance to transmit calls
regularly to a particular telephone at a specified time of day.
Callers trying to reach someone with a personal number would be told
automatically whether they had to make a long-distance call to do so.
Mr Maynard expects the market for personal numbering services to exceed
Pounds 100m in five years. At present, Mercury plans to offer its service
only in Britain but is exploring the possibility of delivering calls
internationally.
Backers of personal numbering say it would have advantages over mobile
telephones, because calls could be received on telephones of any kind. The
planned services would also be much more flexible and easier to use than
existing computerised call-forwarding services.
Mr Stanley White of IIISS, a US group which plans to offer a personal
numbering service in Britain, says it will be 'the darling of the 1990s, as
cellular telephony was in the 1980s'.
US telephone companies recently began offering personal numbering on a
limited basis.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
