<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 92 / Property fears on Sunday trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REMOVAL OF restrictions on Sunday trading might inflict 'real and
long-lasting' damage to the value of retail property and impose added
pressure on town centres, according to an academic study.
Unrestricted Sunday trading would raise labour and other costs more than it
would increase turnover, and in consequence restrict the funds available to
pay rents, according to an article in the Journal of Property Valuation and
Investment. Eventually it might force weaker retailers out of business,
leading to an excess supply of retail sites, which would put continued
pressure on rents.
Town centre shops, particularly those outside the prime shopping areas,
would be most vulnerable, according to the study. They would, it is feared,
lose market share to out-of-town shopping centres, which are more
leisure-oriented and so would be most likely to benefit from family shopping
on Sundays.
Mr Richard Barkham of the University of Reading said his research showed
that deregulation of Sunday trading laws was 'not in the long-term
commercial interests of most retailers, insurance and property companies and
the pension funds'. He added: 'A further expansion of capacity which will
lead to an increase in costs but not turnover will simply prolong this
depression in the retail investment market.'
The effect of unrestricted Sunday trading on the spatial pattern of retail
rents. Journal of Property Valuation and Investment, 2-3 Cornwall Terrace,
Regents Park, London NW1 4QP.
</TEXT>
