FT  03 AUG 92 / Most employers found to flout disabled quotas law
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANY employers flout legislation designed to promote jobs for disabled
people and get away with it, according to a report out today
Three quarters of employers, some 25,000, fail to ensure that 3 per cent of
their staff are registered disabled, says the report published by the
independent Employment Policy Institute.
It is not an offence to be under quota but it is for companies below quota
to recruit a new non-disabled worker.
The law is undermined by exemption certificates, poor monitoring and
under-registration of disabled people, the report says. There have been 10
prosecutions since the law was passed in 1944.
The report says rigid government definitions of unemployment 'hide' high
unemployment among disabled people and therefore cover up widespread
discrimination against them by employers.
The official monthly count of those out of work and claiming unemployment
benefit excludes many disabled people.
Mr Patrick McLoughlin, employment minister, has urged employers to review
recruitment and promotion policies to guard against discrimination. His
comments came after a report found that Asian and young black people have
more difficulty in getting a job than white counterparts.
Against the Odds, Research Management Branch, Department of Employment,
Sheffield S1 4PQ. Pounds 5.
Disabled in the Labour Market. Economic Report Volume 7. Employment Policy
Institute, Southbank House, Black Prince Road, London SE1 7SJ. Tel: 071 735
0777. Pounds 3.
</TEXT>
