<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 92 / Secrecy review by accountants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INSTITUTE of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales is considering
opening its disciplinary proceedings to the public after recent criticism
over secrecy.
A paper to be submitted to the institute's council lists options for opening
some parts of its hearings to observers.
Concern has arisen that wider public access might jeopardise free and frank
provision of evidence. Other worries include issues of defamation, contempt
and breach of confidentiality over the details of the material being
discussed.
Officials emphasise that very few other professional bodies make their
disciplinary hearings public, and do not face the complex questions posed by
proceedings against accountants, in which sensitive information about their
work for clients might be disclosed.
Even so, institute members have come under pressure for more openness on
disciplinary matters from individuals including Mr Douglas Llambias, a
member of the council and of its disciplinary committee.
Mr Llambias was recently refused access to the committee considering the
case against two partners from Coopers &amp; Lybrand in connection with an
alleged breach of ethical codes in their appointment as administrators to
Polly Peck International.
The recommendations follow a series of other reforms to disciplinary
proceedings in recent months, including much stiffer fines, simplified
administration, the appointment of an independent ombudsman and greater
willingness to announce that an investigation is taking place.
</TEXT>
