<HEADLINE>
FT  01 AUG 92 / Channel 4 fined for refusing to disclose source
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE and RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHANNEL 4 yesterday escaped possible sequestration of its assets and the
threat of closure for refusing to reveal the source behind a television
documentary on Northern Ireland.
Instead Lord Justice Woolf imposed a total fine of Pounds 75,000 on the
channel and Box Productions, the company which produced Committee, a
programme alleging systematic collusion between the Royal Ulster
Constabulary and Loyalist death squads.
Channel 4 and Box, which argued that they could not identify their main
source without endangering his life, will decide how to share out the fine.
They will also have to pay costs estimated at between Pounds 150,000 and
Pounds 200,000.
Lord Justice Woolf said in the High Court that Channel 4, which was found to
be in contempt under the Prevention of Terrorism Act, should have borne in
mind that the programme would undermine the reputation of the RUC and the
rule of law  - just what terrorists were trying to do.
He had decided against sequestration of assets, which could have destroyed
Channel 4 and Box, because it was clear they were not going to disclose the
name of 'Source A'.
No one could doubt the dilemma the companies faced or their desire to
co-operate with the law so far as they were able, the judge said. The fine
was therefore substantially smaller than it might have been.
Even more significantly Lord Justice Woolf said there should be no further
proceedings either against the companies or any individuals involved. Sir
Richard Attenborough, Channel 4 chairman, said the judges had recognised the
company's dilemma.
'Although they had no real option but to fine the companies for contempt,
and although there remains a gulf between the views we and the court take on
the duties of serious journalists, no draconian penalties were levied.'
Lord Justice Woolf hoped both companies would reconsider their positions.
While accepting they had a genuine dilemma, it was of their own making.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
