<HEADLINE>
FT  01 AUG 92 / International Company News: Charge for job cuts brings loss
at Aetna
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A SHARPER-than-expected deterioration in property-related investments
contributed to a second-quarter loss of Dollars 20.1m after tax at Aetna
Life &amp; Casualty, one of the largest US composite insurers.
The result compares with a Dollars 159.5m profit in the same period of 1991,
and leaves Aetna with a net profit of Dollars 187.1m for the first six
months of 1992, against Dollars 296.9m in the previous year. Its shares
closed Dollars 1 3/8 lower at Dollars 43 1/4 yesterday.
The loss is struck after a Dollars 145m charge to cover job cuts and
restructuring moves, which Aetna announced last month. The insurer is aiming
to cut staff by 4,800  - about 10 per cent of its workforce. It claims this
should lead to annual after-tax savings of around Dollars 132m by 1994.
Net realised capital losses in the second quarter totalled Dollars 41m,
against a loss of Dollars 12m a year earlier.
However, within this overall figure, additions to reserves for troubled
mortgage loans and property write-downs were Dollars 105m (Dollars 78m),
Partly offsetting this damage were gains of Dollars 76m (Dollars 71m),
largely from sales of bonds and shares.
'We saw more deterioration than we expected in our mortgage loan portfolio
during our normal review process,' admitted Mr Ronald Compton, chairman.
'Most of the deterioration was in the commercial office sector in New
England, California and New York City.
'We adjusted our reserves accordingly and we cannot currently estimate the
full-year impact real estate will have on our earnings.'
The second-quarter figures were also struck after a Dollars 30m charge
related to an Olympia &amp; York financial guarantee  - of which Aetna had also
previously warned.
In terms of operating divisions, the biggest loss (after reorganisation
charges and investment losses) was seen in the commercial property-casualty
business  - a Dollars 37.4m deficit compared with a Dollars 43.1m profit a
year earlier.
The personal property-casualty division turned in Dollars 21.2m deficit
(against a loss of Dollars 2.1m), while financial services made a loss of
Dollars 25.2m (Dollars 35.2m loss).
The life and health business made a profit of Dollars 31m (Dollars 87.5m),
and discontinued operations  - the American Re-Insurance subsidiary which
Aetna is selling to a Kohlberg, Kravis Roberts-backed buyout  - made Dollars
30.9m (Dollars 33.8m).
</TEXT>
