FT  01 AUG 92 / UK Company News: Losses increase to Pounds 125m at Airedale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AIREDALE, the private holding company for the Magnet kitchen retailing
business, fell further into the red with pre-tax losses of Pounds 125m for
the year to March 28.
The result, which compared with a loss of Pounds 119m the previous year, was
struck on sales 17 per cent down at Pounds 187m.
Mr Louis Sherwood, chairman, said 'highly-successful' cost-cutting had
helped to cushion operating losses which rose from Pounds 23.5m to Pounds
27m.
Net interest charges were similar at Pounds 94.7m (Pounds 95.3m). Airedale,
which owes about Pounds 664.2m to bankers following the highly-leveraged
management buy-out of Magnet in 1989, earned some Pounds 3.6m on cash
deposits.
Mr Sherwood said there had been little actual interest paid during the year.
Under current financing arrangements, capital and interest payments on the
company's loans are rolled up until the end of December.
'In light of recent discussions with the group's senior lenders,' Mr
Sherwood said, he was ' confident that satisfactory arrangements will be put
in place well before then.
Magnet, Airedale's operating company, remained financially sound with net
assets of Pounds 160m, a healthy cash balance and no debt, Mr Sherwood said.
The subsidiary is shielded from its parent's debts through an arrangement
with bankers. Until Magnet forecasts a positive cash balance of Pounds 30m
for the following six months, it cannot help pay Airedale's debt or
interest.
Mr Sherwood said steps had been taken to stem losses in Airedale's retail
business. The trade division had moved back into profit, although on lower
sales.
The pre-tax figure included a Pounds 3.4m exceptional item arising from the
introduction of new bedroom ranges.
In view of the capital structure of the company, said Mr Sherwood, an
earnings per share figure would have little relevance. There was no
dividend.
Airedale also faces a claim from GE Capital, which is pressing for repayment
of Pounds 70m mezzanine debt.
The loan was part of Pounds 629m provided for the Magnet MBO. Mr Sherwood
said the group would 'defend the actions vigorously'.
</TEXT>
