<HEADLINE>
FT  01 AUG 92 / Doctors faulted over drug allocation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH doctors prescribe fewer, older and cheaper drugs than their
Continental counterparts, but their prescribing practice is not
cost-effective, according to the Association of the British Pharmaceutical
Industry.
'The UK is not using new medicines wisely,' Dr John Griffin, association
director, said. 'British doctors are using old, slightly more dangerous and
certainly less effective products which are more expensive in the long
term.'
In 1990, the UK pharmaceutical market, including over-the-counter
non-prescription drugs, was Ecu 4.74bn (Pounds 3.4bn). That compared with
Ecu 10.1bn in Germany, and Ecu 8.9bn in France.
UK patients received more than 460m prescriptions last year, up 24m on 1990.
They cost the National Health Service Pounds 3.1bn, representing 9.7 per
cent of its total expenditure. Per capita expenditure on prescription drugs
in the UK is nearly half that in France and Italy, Dr Griffin said. UK per
capita expenditure on prescription drugs in 1990 was only Pounds 55. That
compared with Pounds 105 in Italy, Pounds 102 in France, Pounds 95 in
Germany and Pounds 82 in Sweden.
British GPs prescribe fewer drugs than many of their Continental
counterparts. Prescriptions per capita in the UK averaged only 7.6 in 1989
compared with 38 in France, 20 in Italy and 12 in Germany. Danish, Swedish
and Dutch doctors signed fewer prescriptions.
Drugs prescribed by UK doctors also tend to be old, he said. In Italy,
Japan, the US and Canada, more than 20 per cent of drugs prescribed have
been introduced in the past five years. In the UK, the figure is 9.3 per
cent.
Dr Griffin blamed government measures for making doctors more
cost-conscious. He argued that by prescribing less effective drugs, doctors
were raising overall costs because of increased hospital admissions.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 5
</PAGE>
