<HEADLINE>
FT  01 AUG 92 / Arts: Sculpture of the 'savages' - Susan Moore admires a
Parisian celebration of Black African art
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SUSAN MOORE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN THE 19th century, the Nazarenes in Germany and the Pre-Raphaelites and
their precursors in England looked to the art of the so-called Primitives as
a means of regenerating the art - and society - of the present. In panels
and frescoes painted before the invention of complex illusionistic devices
of lighting and perspective, they found a sincerity and vigour deemed
lacking in contemporary art. The group of 'Primitifs' in JL David's studio
in Paris had similarly rejected the polished classicism of their day and
advocated a return to a simpler form of art.
A century later, comparable reaction to the facile virtuosity of Salon
painting and the over-attenuated decadence of Art Nouveau prompted the Paris
avant-garde to appropriate African sculpture. Its formal language and
expressive power provided a way out of the perceived impasse of Western
realism.
To ethnologists such as the late William Fagg, it was a 'rude
misappropriation'. The Modernists had never been interested in learning from
the tribal art that was gradually filling up the new ethnographical museums
of Europe. They had simply seized on one of the most conservative and
traditional of arts to serve their anarchic and iconoclastic ends.
Certainly the Fauves, Cubists and members of Der Blaue Reiter seemed to care
little about the function or significance of African sculpture, or to
distinguish between works of art and something knocked out for the tourist
trade. It is, however, primarily thanks to these artists that objects which
were initially viewed as curiosities or artefacts made their way out of the
ethnographical museum and into the art gallery. In 1920, the critic Roger
Fry, reviewing an exhibition of Negro art in London, probably spoke for an
entire shocked and bedazzled generation when he felt forced to admit that
so-called savages had produced sculpture that was greater than anything
produced here, even during the Middle Ages.
It is purely on aesthetic grounds that we are invited to admire the 65
choice pieces of Black African sculpture selected by Ezio Bassani currently
on loan to the Musee Dapper in Paris. This exhibition, a version of that
shown at the Forte Belvedere in Florence in 1989, is not meant to be
comprehensive or didactic. It is a celebration of masterpieces.
To that end, considerable care has been taken to show each piece to its best
advantage, in both this beautifully, if somewhat theatrically lit exhibition
and in its lavish catalogue. (Le Grand Heritage: Sculptures de L'Africa
Noire, Fondation Dapper, FFr263).
This delectable visual feast opens with a small section of ancient or early
sculptures, from Akan terracotta heads and Benin bronzes to the extravagant
Afro-Portuguese ivory salts made by the Sapi peoples in Sierra Leone
1490-1530. Disappointingly, there is not one of the great Ife heads that
rank among the finest sculptures ever made. The first of many compensations
is the imposing and imaginatively stylised Nok terracotta head from
500BC-AD200 Nigeria, glinting with the specks of mica ingeniously fired in
its clay. Its technical sophistication seems even more wondrous when one
realises that this head was probably once part of a life-size figure.
Such is the innate vitality of these and many of the more recent figures and
masks that they seem to be imbued with a life of their own. It makes no
difference whether the sculpture is naturalistic and particularly expressive
of personality, or simplified and abstracted to the austere geometries of
Mbole and Ngbaka wooden masks and to the Mahongwe and Kota bronze reliquary
figures from Gabon. No wonder the Modernists looked on covetously.
The representation of the human figure is the predominant theme of African
sculpture. We find ancestor figures created to make contact with the world
of the dead and to affirm the right to land or power, and images of spirits
or divinities which are characterised by their frontality, a rigorous
symmetry and, not infrequently, a considerable serenity and dignity. It is
in the ritual masks, however, that the sculptors seem to be allowed their
greatest freedom of expression.
Bassani has purposely restricted his selection in order to demonstrate the
richly varied modes of expression adopted by individual ethnic groups. The
show is, more generally, glorious witness to the African sculptors' formal
inventiveness and to his instinctive ability to conceive form in three
dimensions, emphasising or diminishing volume at whim to create the desired
rhythm and effect.
A piece such as the remarkable Bangwa seated figure from Cameroon, like all
the best sculptures, is interesting from almost every angle and compels us
around it. The sculptor showed no qualms about massively elongating the
heavily bangled left arm that supports the head: he wanted his figure to
remain appropriately erect.
Perhaps even more extraordinary to our Modernist-trained eyes is the economy
of the top of a headpiece used by members of the Ogbom secret society, where
the figure's torso and flanking arms are reduced to three parallel arcs of
wood of equal width. There is comparably sophisticated use of 'negative'
space in a Kwele mask framed by band of light and air, and in the Mbole
figures from Zaire.
The latter were hung up on walls as a warning to young initiates of what
would befall them if they betrayed the secrets of their 'Lilwa' society.
Torso, arms and legs have been pared down to the narrowest of rough, tubular
forms. The verticality of these male figures, and the sharp angles of neck,
shoulder, arm and knee joints convincingly evoke the posture of hanged men.
Le Grand Heritage continues at the Musee Dapper, 50 avenue Victor Hugo,
75116 Paris, until September 15. Tel: (1) 45 00 01 50.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIV
</PAGE>
