<HEADLINE>
FT  01 AUG 92 / Finance &amp; The Family: Income rescue delay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARBARA ELLIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EFFORTS to compensate investors who lost money on home income plans have hit
a second, potentially embarrassing, delay with a conflict between insurance
companies and the insurance ombudsman.
Delay is especially significant, because most investors were already over
pension age when they bought the plans, which used a remortgage to buy an
investment bond, with the aim of earning a sizeable income. Many unwittingly
reached the brink of losing their homes when house prices fell crashed,
interest rates rose rocketed and the investment bonds failed to perform as
expected.
Some insurance companies tried to head off complaints by approaching all
plan-holders with offers of compensation, but tended to make up only the
loss on the investment bond, and not the loss on mortgage payments or money
withdrawn for capital spending.
The insurance ombudsman's view is that these payments were often too low.
His own and Lautro's guidelines say that investors should be put back where
they were financially before buying the plan and that payments to cover
distress and the cost of legal advice would be considered.
An investor's acceptance of money 'in full and final settlement' would not
preclude examination, since investors might have accepted an offer through
desperation and might not have been told they could go to the ombudsman.
The insurance companies are unhappy about this. One refused point blank when
the ombudsman asked - as a matter of form - for permission to review a case
where compensation had been paid, according to Peter Tyldesley of the
ombudsman's bureau. However, Tyldesley said this would not stop Dr Julian
Farrand, the ombudsman, dealing with the case. Insurance companies must
comply with his decisions and pay awards worth up to Pounds 100,000 unless
they leave the voluntary scheme, after giving six months' notice.
One of the companies most heavily involved in home income plans was Guardian
Royal Exchange, where marketing manager Ken Franklin said the company was
concerned at being asked to overturn something already agreed.
GRE paid sums of between Pounds 2,000 and Pounds 3,000 to each of 490
investors who bought home income plans from Intercity, a GRE-appointed
representative. GRE offered the money, making up losses on investment bonds
only, after cancelling Intercity's agency on discovering some 'probably
perfectly innocent' irregularities with holding of clients' money, said
Franklin. The insurance ombudsman is currently reviewing 12 of these cases.
'They were not told about the ombudsman because they were not complaining,'
said Franklin, 'We were writing to those customers out of the blue saying we
have looked at these schemes and we are going to make an offer to you.'
'We were one of the first companies to actually get off our butts and do
something,' said Franklin, 'We are not happy to have it looked at again.' He
said GRE was hopeful its discussions with the ombudsman would reach an
amicable solution.
</TEXT>
