<HEADLINE>
FT  01 AUG 92 / Finance &amp; The Family: Think cheap when you choose a company
car
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INLAND Revenue had some dispiriting news for Britain's executives this
week. From now on, it seems, the rule of thumb when choosing a company car
will be - go for the cheapest.
Many drivers could gain if proposals to reform income tax treatment for
company cars - contained in a new consultative paper - are enacted. Tax
bills could be cut by as much as 30 per cent, although some may go up by
more than 40 per cent.
The reforms will not operate until the beginning of the 1994-95 tax year at
the earliest, and the Revenue could yet make changes. But if you are
choosing a company car in the next few months, it would be foolish not to
bear these plans in mind.
The present system lumps cars into broad bands according to their engine
size if their price is below Pounds 19,250. The new rules would tax cars
entirely on their price, and would have far more bands.
There are, however, several ways in which price could be assessed. At
present, the Revenue favours the manufacturer's retail list price, but other
possibilities include the cost to the employer and the original market
value.
Some accountants, including Martin Myerscough of Arthur Andersen, also are
worried that the new administrative burdens on companies, and the costly
consequences of making mistakes, will discourage some from offering company
cars altogether - heaping further gloom onto Britain's executives.
Precise gains and losses cannot be determined until the new rules are more
definite. But those affected worst are likely to be drivers of cars with
engines just below two litres and which fall just within the Pounds 19,455
limit. Tax bills for them could increase by up to 40 per cent, but they have
been benefiting from the present system.
Shed a tear, also, for executives with cars costing between Pounds 50,000
and Pounds 60,000. Their tax could increase by around 35 per cent.
If your company has bought you a cheap but powerful car, such as a Vauxhall
Astra or Ford Fiesta, expect to benefit by anything up to 25 per cent. All
the precise details will be announced in the Budget next March.
Several experts are hoping for changes, as well as extra detail, by then but
Clive Tulloch, tax partner with accountant Coopers &amp; Lybrand, said the
Revenue had missed several opportunities to remove anomalies in the system.
He pointed out that the proportion of the scale charge on a car which
individuals must pay will still be based on their business mileage. This is
bad news for those with very high annual distances covered who need their
cars most.
According to Tulloch, those with annual business mileages of somewhere
between 12,000 and 15,000 miles at the bottom, and 17,999 at the top, would
be better off taking additional cash from their employer and buying their
own car.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
