<HEADLINE>
FT  01 AUG 92 / Markets: At a Glance - Underlying problems worsen in the
housing market
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The underlying problems of the housing market are getting steadily worse and
mortgage repossessions are set to run at alarming levels for the next few
years. That was the bleak message from the Council of Mortgage Lenders this
week. Although the number of homes repossessed in the first half of this
year was slightly down, the figures for people with serious mortgage arrears
are rising sharply.
The number of people with mortgage arrears of more than 12 months has
tripled since the end of 1990 and now stands at 113,860. A further 191,280
borrowers are more than six months behind with their mortgage payments. Even
if half are saved, as the CML hopefully predicts, it now seems certain that
repossessions could continue to run at around last year's level of 75,540 or
more for the next two or three years.
</TEXT>
