<HEADLINE>
FT  01 AUG 92 / Commodities and Agriculture (Week in the markets): Strike
nerves push platinum higher
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD MOONEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NERVOUSNESS ahead of next week's national strike in South Africa pushed
platinum prices up sharply at the end of the week. South Africa accounts for
about two thirds of the total platinum supplies.
An earlier downtrend had been encouraged by Tuesday's announcement that a
pay settlement had been reached between management and unions at Impala
Platinum, South Africa's second biggest producer. But that slide was
reversed on Thursday, when the price rose Dollars 3.75 to Dollars 376.25 a
troy ounce, and yesterday a further Dollars 9 was added, taking the price to
Dollars 385.25 at the afternoon fix, up Dollars 4.90 on the week.
The two-day South African strike that is scheduled to begin on Monday had
already been discounted at the price ruling before the rise of the last two
days, but the market nevertheless became increasingly edgy as it drew
nearer. 'Nobody wanted to go into the weekend short. . . and the early
buying caused a panicky scramble to get covered,' one dealer explained
yesterday. He said there was concern that situation in South Africa might
get out of control once the strike was under way.
The gold price moved up with platinum yesterday, rising Dollars 1.35 to
Dollars 357.95 an ounce, up 50 cents on the week.
At the London Metal Exchange nickel prices came under increasing pressure as
stocks in exchange warehouses surged by 6,924 tonnes to an all-time high of
34,560 tonnes. That compared with 11,922 tonnes at the start of the year and
6,420 tonnes 12 months ago and beat the previous record of 32,664 tonnes set
in March 1984. A decisive breach of support at around Dollars 7,500 a tonne
for three months metal prompted further selling yesterday and by the close
the price was Dollars 7,417.50 a tonne, down Dollars 75 on the day and
Dollars 205 on the week.
The uptrend in LME lead stocks also continued this week, the total rising
another 1,600 tonnes to 148,800 tonnes. But that bearish factor was easily
outweighed by Thursday's news that workers had gone on strike at Doe Run's
Herculaneum smelter in the US, which has an annual capacity of 225,000 short
tons (2,000 lb). The cash price rose immediately by Pounds 17 to Pounds
353.50 a tonne, but was trimmed yesterday to Pounds 349.25, up Pounds 7.25
on the week, as the company said the smelter might restart on Monday, run by
salaried staff.
The announcement of a modest fall in LME aluminium stocks helped prices to
steady a little yesterday following a run of chart-inspired losses earlier
in the week. The cash price closed at Dollars 1,316.50 a tonne, up Dollars 6
on the day but Dollars 21 down on the week.
Some traders said that the flood of Russian aluminium that had driven the
exchange stockpile to unprecedented levels over the past 18 months had
slowed to a trickle as production difficulties got the better of the
country's hard-pressed producers. Shortages of cash, alumina (aluminium
oxide) and spare parts, combined with transport difficulties suggested that
Russian claims that exports were being maintained at 75 per cent of last
year's level (estimated at 1m tonnes) would not stand close examination,
they said.
Despite concern about Polish copper workers' plans to intensify their strike
action against the KGHM combine copper prices declined for most of the week.
A fall in LME stocks aided a Pounds 6.50 rally yesterday, however, and the
cash price closed at Pounds 1,315.50 a tonne, Pounds 25 down on the week.
When three months delivery tin breached the Dollars 7,000-a-tonne level on
Monday traders suggested that with chart patterns looking bearish a further
slide was on the cards. And they were not disappointed. Despite recovering
Dollars 20 yesterday the price ended the week Dollars 207.50 down on balance
at Dollars 6,835 a tonne.
The coffee market got little inspiration from talks going on in London this
week on a new price-stabilising international coffee agreement and the
September futures price ended Dollars 8 down on balance at Dollars 745 a
tonne.
'If you look at what has happened over the past week, then we haven't
achieved much. The prevailing feeling is one of frustration,' producer
spokesman Mr Valdemar Carneiro Leao of Brazil told the Reuter news agency
yesterday. The producers' disappointment stems from what they regard as the
inflexibility of certain consumers on the issue of controls. In particular
they are concerned that leading consumers such as the US are prepared to
accept coffee without proper documentation. Producers feel consumers should
be more committed to controlling imports at their end.
