<HEADLINE>
FT  01 AUG 92 / UK Company News: Dollars 913m agreed bidfor Templeton,
Galbraith
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TEMPLETON, Galbraith Hansberger, the London-listed and Bahamas-based
international fund management company, is being acquired by Franklin
Resources Incorporated, the California-based fund manager in an agreed deal
valued at Dollars 913m (Pounds 478m).
Franklin specialises in fixed-income retail products and the merger will
form the largest independent fund management company in the US.
The merger is widely viewed as a bellwether for the mutual fund industry
which is facing increasing competition in a mature market. Selling expenses
are rising and industry analysts are taking the view that further
consolidation within the industry is likely.
'Fund managers will need to have more money under management in order to
cover costs,' said Mr Patrick Donlea, partner at Cazenove which acted as
adviser on the transaction.
The deal is expected to give Templeton access to greater distribution
networks in the US, said Mr Martin Flanagan, a director of TGH. Templeton
recently announced changes to its pricing structure, lowering front-end fees
on its mutual funds because they were substantially above the industry
average and were costing the company sales.
The terms call for Sir John Templeton, the 79-year old founding member of
the company, his son Mr John Templeton and partner Mr John Galbraith to
receive Dollars 5.69 per share. The three own about 70 per cent of the
company.
Sir John has said he would like gradually to reduce his involvement in the
company's affairs and will change his role in the new structure to that of
consultant.
Public shareholders will receive Dollars 6 a share. Because of the deal, no
dividends will be paid in respect of the six month period ended June 30
1992.
If Templeton loses more than 20 per cent of its funds under management
before the deal can be approved by shareholders then the price per share
will fall. If more than 40 per cent of funds under management are withdrawn,
both Templeton and Franklin have the right to terminate the agreement.
Franklin said its intention was to keep the management structure and
investment style of Templeton intact - a key factor in retaining Templeton's
client base. To this end, it plans to offer employment contracts, which
include bonuses, to certain employees, including four of the directors. Two
of the four are Mr Thomas Hansberger and Mr J Mark Mobius, investment
manager of the highly successful emerging markets fund. If the directors
stay a further two years after the merger, they will receive another Dollars
32m in bonuses.
</TEXT>
