FT  01 AUG 92 / UK Company News: OMI incurs Pounds 2.7m loss and shares fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES of OMI International fell 5p to 12p yesterday after the design,
instrumentation, and electro-optics group announced heavy losses and the
sale of businesses.
OMI, formerly called Optical and Medical International, made pre-tax losses
of Pounds 2.68m in the year to March 31, compared with profits of Pounds
2.45m last time. Turnover was Pounds 51.21m (Pounds 53.48m).
The group has agreed to sell its aerospace and general design businesses and
the staff placement agency business, OTS Services, to Hebron &amp; Medlock
(Holdings), a private company. The deal will bring OMI a net Pounds 2m in
cash, but the group made an extraordinary provision of Pounds 12.82m,
principally to cover the disposals. Also included in the extraordinary
provision were the costs of closing parts of Peters &amp; Zabranbsky, a German
subsidiary.
Mr Gil Williams, chairman and chief executive, said this exit from the
depressed aerospace and general design businesses was part of the group's
strategy of focusing on specialised products and added-value services - such
as industrial logistics, diagnostics and optronics.
Losses per share of 6.4p compared with a profit of 3.4p last time. At the
year-end, OMI had net cash of Pounds 478,000, which will be boosted by the
proceeds of the disposals. In view of the strength of the balance sheet, the
board recommended a final dividend of 1p, giving a total for the year of
1.75p (5.21p).
