<HEADLINE>
FT  01 AUG 92 / Letter: Devaluation is no answer, and 'siren voices' must be
resisted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr MATTHEW BRODRICK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Those calling for a sterling devaluation, in the hope of allowing
domestic interest rates to fall, are surely overlooking the consequences for
the UK's balance of payments, and the short- and long-term effects on
British exporters.
In the short term, a sterling devaluation will have the effect of reducing
export earnings - foreign demand for British goods will not suddenly jump
overnight because those goods are perceived to be cheaper.
In the longer term, such is the British propensity to import, any recovery
will lead to the inevitable increase in demand for foreign goods, but at a
higher price relative to the size of any devaluation. These domestic
inflationary pressures will have to be offset, most probably through the use
of higher interest rates. Additionally, export earnings will only recover
should expenditure switching be possible, and foreign purchasers can find
British goods which are suitable substitutes for foreign ones.
The UK economy would therefore have gone full circle, firstly depressing the
export earnings of industry, and secondly by offsetting inflationary
pressures from imported price rises through the use of higher interest
rates. For this, British industry would not thank the present government if
it ceded to the 'siren voices'.
Matthew Brodrick,
Top Floor Flat,
48 Alma Vale Road,
Clifton, Bristol BS8 2HS
</TEXT>
