FT  31 JUL 92 / Labour renews attack over jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR launched a fresh attack on the government's record on jobs yesterday
when it claimed that the Tories had failed to deliver 10,000 promised places
on their Employment Action programme, Ivo Dawnay writes.
The onslaught was a first shot in the opposition's summer offensive. The
shadow economic team charged the government with a 'callous betrayal' of the
unemployed.
Labour said in a statement released by Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor,
that Mr Michael Howard, when employment secretary, had committed the
government to finding work experience places for 60,000 people and to having
30,000 people on schemes at any time.
Yet in May, two months after a target deadline, some 10,000 places had
remained unfilled. 'In many constituencies there are as many as 10,000
people unemployed, with sometimes as few as 30 places on Employment Action
available,' the statement said.
