<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JUL 92 / London Stock Exchange: Market excited by ICI news
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By COLIN MILLHAM, CHRISTOPHER PRICE and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SHOCK news that ICI was considering demerging its businesses
overshadowed the chemical group's disappointing interim results and sent the
share price soaring. Opening at 1095p, the stock rose rapidly, touching
1229p before declining in hectic dealings to close a net 76 ahead at 1171p
with a hefty 14m traded.
Chemicals observers were most excited by the prospect of the proposed ICI
Bio group, which would include ICI's pharmaceutical, agrochemical, seed and
specialty chemical businesses, believing it would pave the way for further
merger or acquisition opportunities in these industries. For this reason,
Fisons, long tipped as a potential partner for ICI's drugs and agrochemical
interests, rose 10 to 173p with a substantial 9.5m dealt.
While details of the plan are scarce, Mr Martin Glen at Lehman Brothers says
he would put an initial value on the new ICI of 1250p, giving ICI Bio an
earnings per share of 15p and the new ICI one of 10p.
The excitement overshadowed ICI's interim report, which pointed to
continuing tough trading conditions and, somewhat ironically, the poor
showing by the pharmaceutical and agrochem divisions. Lehman cut its
forecast for this year by Pounds 50m to Pounds 800m and for 1993 by Pounds
80m to Pounds 920m. Kleinwort Benson is on similar ground, forecasting
Pounds 805m and Pounds 920m respectively.
Marks placing
Traders were impressed when the market absorbed a very large placing of
21.15m shares in Marks and Spencer without too much problem yesterday. The
shares were placed by Cazenove at 305p on behalf of trustees in the Marks
and Spencer pension fund, which was reacting to professional advice against
pension scheme investment in shares of its own company. On turnover of 43m,
Marks finished 8 lower at 311p.
Legislation requires a pension fund to reduce any equity holding in its own
company to less than 5 per cent by March 1994. Before yesterday's placing,
Mark's pension fund held 24m shares in the company, representing about 7 per
cent of its total assets by value. It retains a holding of 2.85m shares.
The last set of interim figures from Midland Bank, now under the control of
Hongkong and Shanghai Banking (HSBC), caused only the merest flicker in HSBC
shares, which eased 1 1/2 to 335 1/2 p on 8.2m turnover.
Lloyds Bank, reporting first-half figures this morning, gained 5 to 424p,
but National Westminster dipped 5 to 325p and Barclays 3 to 319p.
Dealings commenced in TransAtlantic, the life assurance company which took
over Sun Life. The shares were initially quoted below the 190p mark but
gradually improved to end a very quiet debut session at 195p.
Widespread bad publicity regarding water quality inspired some persistent
selling of Thames Water, 7 off at 405p. Other poor performers in the sector
included Anglian Water, 6 down at 388p, North West, 5 cheaper at 412p, and
Yorkshire, 9 weaker at 428p.
Suggestions that James Capel, the agency broker, had been recommending a
switch out of the Scottish generators into National Power and PowerGen
triggered some big activity in the sector. National (239p) and PowerGen
(251p) added 4 each, but Scottish Power retreated 5 to 184p and Scottish
Hydro eased to 204 1/2 p.
Heavy US buying of BP died away, the shares slipping 2 1/2 to 214p after an
initial level of 218p. Turnover reached 9m. Shell also ran into a flurry of
small but persistent selling, closing a net 3 off at 466p.
Lasmo was heavily traded, with 7.9m shares changing hands, and the stock was
finally a shade off at 133p.
Bad publicity over the group's oil and gas acquisitions in Kazakhstan saw
British Gas dip 2 1/2 to 246 1/2 p on turnover of 8.5m shares.
Cable and Wireless ran up strongly to close 12 higher at 537p, with the
market said to be responding to a bullish view of the stock adopted by
broker Strauss Turnbull.
MicroFocus forged ahead 45 to 1715p, with demand stimulated by the strong
performance of Wall Street in recent sessions.
British Aerospace staged a strong rally after the heavy selling induced by
worries about the group's long-term strategy. Stimulated by a handful of buy
notes, notably one from leading research house County NatWest, the shares
climbed 11 to 206p, with dealers still aware of hints that GEC may be
lurking in the background as a potential predator.
Property shares were again under pressure as an abundance of stock hit the
leading issues. Hammerson 'A' tumbled 26 to 213p, Great Portland Estates 7
to 110p and British Land 3 to 168p. MEPC lost 17 to 226p, with turnover
boosted by a late trade of 4.4m shares at 210p, believed to have been a bed
and breakfast, or tax-related, deal.
Hotel group Forte bounced after positive comments to analysts that some
parts of the hotel market were showing signs of resilience, and also news of
a large contract awarded to its subsidiary Gardner Merchant. The shares
rallied 6 to 150p.
The brewing and drinks sector was generally weak, with Grand Metropolitan
losing 8 to 415p after a small downward revision in its profits forecast by
Lehman Brothers. The US securities house remained positive on the stock,
however, saying that any weakness in GrandMet's US food operations is likely
to be offset by benefits in the international spirits trade. Guinness
slipped 12 to 532p, while Bass shed 7 to 538p.
Allied-Lyons' performance was relatively more positive, after this week's
decision that its brewing deal with Carlsberg will go ahead in spite of the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission's modifications to the agreement. The
shares finished just  1/2 off at 615p.
Regional brewer Gibbs Mew, an unlisted security, jumped 30 to 168p on an
'unsolicited approach' by Brierley Investments, which said it is considering
making an offer, although no price or terms have been indicated.
Hepworth, the building products group, added 4 at 310p after interim figures
above City forecasts. But expectations of a big bounce in the building
materials sector proved premature. RMC remained under constant pressure and
fell 12 to 489p.
Mirror Group Newspapers held at 69p but turnover, which stalled on Wednesday
after a series of heavy trading sessions, began to pick up again. By the
close of business yesterday some 3.3m shares had changed hands, with a block
of 1.2m traded late in the session at 68p.
