<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JUL 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow higher in spite of
retreating bond prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US EQUITIES managed to finish moderately higher yesterday after shrugging
off a mixed bag of economic news, a downturn in the domestic bond market and
lower stock markets in Europe, writes Karen Zagor in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average added 12.70 at 3,391.89 after the previous
two-day upsurge of 97 points. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 eclipsed Wednesday's
record level, ending 1.69 stronger at 423.92, while the Nasdaq composite
appreciated 1.31 to 578.80.
Turnover on the New York SE was a fairly heavy 193.4m shares, but well below
the previous day's 276m. Equities put on a reasonable performance in the
face of a retreat by the bond market, where the benchmark 30-year issue lost
ground through most of the day before turning slightly higher in late
trading.
There was little reaction to economic news, which included a larger than
expected fall in unemployment claims for the week ended July 18, a
surprisingly strong improvement in new home sales for June, an unexpectedly
low reading for second quarter Gross Domestic Product and an encouraging
inflation report.
Equimark soared in NYSE trading after the Pennsylvania commercial banking
group said it had agreed to be acquired by Integra Financial through a
Dollars 296m stock swap. Equimark's stock was quoted at Dollars 6 5/8 , up
Dollars 1 1/8 , while Integra fell Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 36 1/8 in Nasdaq
trading.
ICI ADRs jumped Dollars 5 5/8 to Dollars 89 3/4 . The UK chemical company
reported a 33 per cent decline in second quarter pre-tax earnings and said
it might spin off its bioscience division.
Alliant Techsystems tumbled Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 21 3/8 on the back of
first quarter earnings from continuing operations of 59 cents a share, down
from Dollars 1.58 a year earlier.
UAL, parent of United Airlines, advanced Dollars 3 1/2 to Dollars 114 in
spite of a second quarter loss of Dollars 3.94 a share, compared with
earnings of Dollars 2.23 a year earlier. AMR, parent of American Airlines,
gained Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 67 1/8 and Delta Airlines rose Dollars 1 to
Dollars 56.
Canada
TORONTO ended a shade firmer after moderate trading. The TSE 300 index
gained just 1.0 at 3,425.6 and rises held a small lead over declines by 288
to 243 after volume of 24.3m shares valued at CDollars 226.2m.
PWA, which plunged CDollars 2.92 over the past two sessions, picked up 26
cents to CDollars 2.34. The drop in the share price was sparked by the
failure of its talks with American Airlines, and the belief that Air Canada
might buy the best assets of PWA's Canadian Airlines unit, leaving little
for shareholders. Air Canada regained 5 cents to CDollars 5.
Noranda, up CDollars  1/8 at CDollars 19 3/8 , announced higher second
quarter and six-month earnings and a regular quarterly dividend of 25 cents;
there had been rumors that a dividend cut was being considered.
</TEXT>
