<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JUL 92 / International Company News: UAL blames fare wars for Dollars
95.1m loss in quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UAL, the parent company of United Airlines, joined its two big US rivals in
reporting a large loss for the second quarter of 1992, and warned it expects
poor results for the balance of the year.
The carrier also hinted that further cost-cutting measures may be
implemented.
UAL said it lost Dollars 95.1m after tax in the three-month period, against
a profit of Dollars 52.7m in the same period of 1991. This takes UAL's loss
for the first six months of 1992 to Dollars 187.4m, a sharp rise on the
Dollars 104.3m deficit seen in the first half of 1991.
At the operating level, UAL's deficit for the quarter totalled Dollars
73.9m, compared with profits of Dollars 63.7m a year ago. Revenues were up
from Dollars 3.14bn, compared with Dollars 2.95bn in 1991, but yield, in
terms of revenue per passenger mile, fell from 12.28 cents to 12.14 cents.
In common with American and Delta - United's two main rivals - the
Chicago-based carrier pinned the blame on the early summer's ferocious
domestic fare wars.
Mr Stephen Wolf, chairman, said: 'Our clearly unsatisfactory results reflect
the severe impact of revenue-dilutive pricing activity in the US, as well as
the effects of the recessionary environment throughout much of the world.'
Ominously, Mr Wolf warned that this situation could persist throughout 1992:
'We expect these same factors to have a negative effect on our results for
at least the balance of 1992,' he said.
And he suggested action to reduce costs might be necessary. 'Unless this
situation is reversed, alternative actions to reduce our expenses will have
to be considered,' he warned.
United has already announced it will cut at least Dollars 2bn from its
Dollars 15.8bn capital spending programme planned for 1992-95.
United is the third 'mega-carrier' to suffer large second-quarter losses.
AMR, the parent company for American Airlines, reported a net loss of
Dollars 166m - or Dollars 48m if one-off charges were excluded. Delta Air
Lines followed with a loss of Dollars 180.2m. Delta accompanied its results
with news of staff reductions, and a general pruning of costs.
Continental Airlines, the fifth largest US carrier, also reported losses
yesterday afternoon.
The carrier, which has been operating under bankruptcy court protection
since late-1990, saw an after-tax loss of Dollars 99.2m in the three months
to end-June, against a Dollars 109.1m deficit in the same period a year
earlier. Revenues were Dollars 1.37bn (Dollars 1.37bn).
Continental's six-month loss now stands at Dollars 81.8m, against a Dollars
290.4m deficit in the first half of 1991. The figures, it said, 'reflected
the impact of fare discounting programmes and relatively weak industry
traffic'.
But, despite the industry's widespread acknowledgement of damage done by
fare wars, Delta Air Lines announced it was slashing 30 per cent off the
price charged for 14-day advance purchase tickets.
This 'Fall Sale' will last throughout August and cover domestic round-trip
travel from September 14 to December 14. After September, Delta said it
would raise all domestic fares by five per cent from their current levels.
Continental Airlines, meanwhile, was reported to have cut coast-to-coast
fares to as little as Dollars 99, while Swissair reduced its fares on
round-trip travel between the US and Switzerland.
</TEXT>
