<PROFILE>_AN-CG4BOAGZFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920731
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JUL 92 / International Company News: Bramalea to default on two debt
payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRAMALEA, the ailing property developer controlled by Toronto's Bronfman
family, is to default on two debt payments while it puts the finishing
touches to a corporate restructuring plan.
The company said yesterday it is negotiating an 'arrangement' with senior
debenture holders under which they would refrain from taking bankruptcy
action against it until at least the end of August. The restructuring is due
to be cleared with all lenders by then.
Bramalea has debts of CDollars 4.9bn (USDollars 4.15bn). Its troubles stem
largely from purchases of undeveloped land, at the peak of the last property
boom. Plans to pay down debt by selling assets have been stalled by the
severe slump in North American real estate markets.
The company said yesterday its five major Canadian bank lenders, as well as
Trizec, its controlling shareholder, have agreed in principle to the terms
of the plan, including providing financial support for the next five years.
The main thorn in Bramalea's side in recent months however, has been its
smaller lenders, including several foreign banks, which have less to lose if
it is forced to file for court protection.
The two debt payments to be skipped are a CDollars 5.2m interest payment on
a series of senior debentures, on which the grace period expired yesterday;
and a principal payment on another series of debentures.
Under the restructuring plan, Bramalea hopes to cut its debt - largely
through asset sales - to about CDollars 2bn by 1997 and to produce a
positive cash flow by next year. It has suspended all dividends.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
