<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JUL 92 / UK Company News: Brierley Investments considers Gibbs Mew
bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRIERLEY Investments Limited, which holds stakes in Budgens, the supermarket
chain, Alvis, the defence contractor, and Mount Charlotte, the hotels group,
yesterday announced that it was considering making an offer for the 80.3 per
cent of Gibbs Mew, the Salisbury-based brewer and commercial property group,
that its subsidiary, BIL Securities (Far East), does not already own.
It said its offer would be at a premium to 138p, Gibbs Mew's share price at
the time of the announcement. Gibbs Mew's shares jumped to 173p, to fall
back to 168p.
The possible offer hinges on certain pre-conditions: that Gibbs Mew's
activities remain as normal; that it makes no disposals or acquisitions; and
that it does not issue or allot any shares.
Last night BIL would not comment further than its statement. Gibbs Mew was
equally reticent.
However, it is thought that a dispute is growing between the USM-quoted
brewer and its biggest non-family shareholder over possible moves the Gibbs
Mew management may be considering and the announcement of BIL's possible bid
is designed to stymie the management plans. Market rumours suggest one such
move might be the acquisition of a business connected with the drinks side
of Gibbs Mew's operations.
Gibbs Mew was founded in the 1850s by the great-grandfather of Mr Peter
Gibbs, the current chairman. Some 58 per cent of the equity is held by Mr
Gibbs, his three daughters and his son.
BIL was founded by Sir Ron Brierley, who was ousted in a boardroom coup in
1989 by Mr Bruce Hancox, the current chairman, and Mr Paul Collins, chief
executive.
</TEXT>
