FT  31 JUL 92 / London economy expected to decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GREATER LONDON will show the weakest economic performance of the main
British regions this year, with a fall in output of 0.8 per cent, according
BSL Business Strategies, an economic consultancy.
Its latest regional outlook forecasts that the UK economy as a whole will
grow by a minimal 0.1 per cent this year. Output will rise slightly in the
second half, with growth of UK gross domestic product quickening to 2.8 per
cent next year. BSL says regional growth differentials will remain
relatively small as growth gets under way, contrasting with experience in
the 1980s.
Mr David Fell, BSL's principal economist, said: 'We do not expect the
re-emergence of a strong north-south divide.'
BSL expects that East Anglia and the north-west will head the regional
growth league this year with GDP increases of 1 per cent and 0.8 per cent
respectively. It believes that the south-east will be the strongest-growing
area in 1993, with 3.3 per cent growth, although within that region Greater
London will continue to perform relatively badly. Greater London's GDP is
expected to grow at the national average rate of 2.8 per cent next year. Job
losses in the capital since 1988 will have totalled 450,000 by next year.
BSL Regional Planning Service, 10 Kendrick Mews, London SW7 3HG.
