<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JUL 92 / Stricter company policing is sought
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CADBURY committee on the financial aspects of corporate governance
should give greater consideration to enforcement, the Institute of Chartered
Accountants of Scotland said yesterday.
The institute called in a submission which broadly supported the Cadbury
report for greater detail on how the Stock Exchange will ensure that
non-compliance with the proposed code is publicised.
It said a number of improvements should be made before the final version of
the report is published later this year. The institute argued that the onus
is on a company's auditor to demonstrate its independence, adding that an
auditor should disclose more information on the services it provides in
addition to auditing, as well as its fees.
The institute said large private companies should be encouraged to abide by
the code, which is directed at public companies. It emphasised the
importance of the need for a continuous review of the effectiveness of
implementation of the code.
The institute added that greater consideration should be given to the
informal ways in which financial information is passed on to analysts, to
ensure that there is equal access for all participants in the market.
The institute also emphasised that Cadbury should steer clear of the idea of
two-tier boards - in which executive and non-executive directors are seen as
working separately - and stress the importance of unitary boards, where the
two work together.
Letters, Page 15
