<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JUL 92 / Businesses report scarcity of skills
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEW skills shortages are emerging that will constrain the UK when it emerges
from recession, according to a survey of large companies.
The survey, by Gallup on behalf of Coopers &amp; Lybrand, the accountancy and
management consultancy firm, indicates that the recession has removed some
of the UK's traditional skills shortages.
But many of the 100 companies polled say they are experiencing difficulties
in specific skills areas where shortages are now almost as severe as before
the recession.
Shortages persist in information technology, languages and managerial,
professional and supervisory skills, they say. Shortages of linguistic
skills have worsened during the recession.
The report says: 'These are precisely the areas where the same companies see
the greatest demands emerging between now and the year 2000.'
Companies, according to the survey, fail to equip individuals with requisite
skills.
Only 50 per cent of companies have, for example, specified the areas of
competence they require of managers.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand say appraisal systems in many companies do not lead to
skills development and are in danger of becoming mere annual rituals. 'That
is in spite of the increasing recognition of the growing demands on
managers,' says the report.
Few companies are equipping older people with the skills needed. 'This could
put the UK's economic survival in jeopardy,' says Coopers &amp; Lybrand. 'The
number of under-35s in the UK workforce is falling, so companies need to
retain older members of staff and make sure that they have the right
skills.'
The survey found that government measures, such as Opportunity 2000 and the
Management Charter Initiative (MCI), had made little impact on companies'
training plans. Miss Sheila Drew Smith, a Coopers &amp; Lybrand partner, said
this may be because the companies in the survey had already developed their
own strategies in these areas.
People Training and Development - The Vision And The Reality. 071-212 4880.
</TEXT>
