FT  31 JUL 92 / Building workloads drop 25%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent and VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSTRUCTION industry criticism of the government's handling of the economy
intensified yesterday after publication of a survey indicating a 25 per cent
fall in work during the past 12 months.
A survey of 1,000 offices of quantity surveyors, by the Royal Institution of
Chartered Surveyors, showed that order books during the three months to the
end of June had fallen by a quarter compared with the same period last year
and by 4.7 per cent compared with the previous three months.
Since much quantity surveying work, like that of architects, occurs early in
the construction process, the findings can be related to the prospects for
the industry as a whole.
Mr Christopher Vickers, a senior partner at EC Harris cost consultants, one
of the largest firms of quantity surveyors, said: 'All we get from ministers
are platitudes. They seem to be unaware of the long-term damage which is
being done to the construction industry.' Mr Vickers said there was
increasing concern that the government would cut capital investment in
construction as a means of controlling public expenditure.
His comments were made ahead of publication today of forecasts from the
National Council of Building Material Producers. They are expected to show a
further sharp fall in construction output and indications that the recovery
will be delayed until 1994.
A separate survey by the Royal Institute of British Architects estimates
that a third of the country's 30,000 registered architects are unemployed or
working below capacity. It says architects' earnings fell by 2 per cent on
average last year to Pounds 23,000, the first decline in cash or real terms
since records began in 1976.
A survey to be published today by the Federation of Civil Engineering
Contractors is expected to reveal a steep decline in expectations since the
general election. It is expected to warn that the outlook for orders and
jobs is the worst for years.
MOST commercial property lenders expect no improvement and even a decline in
the market over the next year, according to a survey of 58 banks and other
financial institutions, Vanessa Houlder writes.
It shows that lenders have revised their forecasts as the expected recovery
has failed to materialise. This month, only 48 per cent expect an
improvement in the market over the next 12 months, down from 55 per cent in
January and 70 per cent in July last year.
The report by Chesterton Financial, a property adviser, and Chartered
Surveyor Weekly magazine suggests that the next six months may be critical
for struggling property companies.
Sixty-nine per cent of those polled expect the upward trend in receiverships
to continue over the next six months. Confidence Barometer. Chesterton
Financial, 54 Brook Street, London W1A 2BU. Free.
