<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JUL 92 / Adjudication urged in gas dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GAS Consumers' Council, which represents 17m gas customers, is calling
on British Gas and the industry regulator Ofgas to refer to the Monopolies
and Mergers Commission their dispute over the rate of return on the gas
pipeline business.
Letters from Mr James Cooper, chairman of the council, were delivered
yesterday to Mr Cedric Brown, who will take over tomorrow as chief executive
of British Gas, and Sir James McKinnon, director-general of Ofgas. Mr Cooper
said he could see no alternative to a wide-ranging inquiry into the
structure of the UK gas industry.
As moves were made towards greater competition in the industry, it was
essential to ensure that public interest was being properly served, he
added. 'There is a risk that the consequence of increased competition will
be higher prices. Such a risk is too great to be accepted without a public
inquiry.'
Mr Cooper suggested that some changes proposed by the government and the
Office of Fair Trading might be 'going too far or too fast', and it was time
for an 'impartial referee' to adjudicate.
Under the terms of an agreement with the OFT, British Gas must hive off its
transportation and storage business into an arm's-length subsidiary by 1994.
A pricing system is due to be published by September.
British Gas insists that it must be allowed to earn an adequate rate of
return from the pipeline business - a return which it puts at 6.7 per cent
on existing assets and 10.8 per cent on new investment. Mr Brown said last
week he did not rule out a referral to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission
if there was no agreement. Sir James is believed to favour a lower return,
although he has yet to respond to British Gas's submission.
The consumers' council says the case for a review of the price cap, which
limits the rise in consumer gas prices to the RPI minus 5 per cent, is
'worryingly strong' while British Gas faces additional costs from its
separate pipeline and storage business. That might result in higher prices.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
</DOC>
