<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JUL 92 / Top Granada executive to head ITV
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR ANDREW QUINN was yesterday named as ITV's first chief executive on a
three-year contract with total remuneration likely to be between Pounds
400,000 and Pounds 500,000 a year.
Mr Quinn, the 55-year-old chief executive of Granada Television - who will
be responsible for an annual budget of about Pounds 500m - said: 'There is
no doubt ITV will have to be more commercial in future. The Independent
Television Commission recognises that.' Mr Quinn emphasised that his
strategy would be: 'If it ain't broke, don't fix it'. But he added that:
Current-affairs programmes would need audiences of 8m to 9m to earn their
slots in prime time. Granada's award-winning World in Action has been
drawing audiences of 7.5m.
Scheduling techniques such as 'stripping' - running the same type of
programme at the same time each evening - was now possible.
He would argue for extension of the definition of prime time from 10.30pm
until 11pm. That might allow News at Ten to run half an hour later if it was
decided that was necessary for scheduling purposes.
Mr Quinn also warned that further rationalisations would be needed in ITV.
'There is a whole duplication in the system with 15 sets of everything.'
The choice of Mr Quinn took ITV right back to the beginning in their search
for a chief executive to run the new centralised network from this autumn.
Mr Quinn was the first choice of senior ITV executives at the beginning of
this year after unofficial approaches to Mr Michael Grade, chief executive
of Channel 4 had been rebuffed.
Then came the internal upheavals at Granada and the forced resignation of Mr
David Plowright, chairman of Granada Television. Mr Quinn decided he could
not leave Granada at such a time.
Headhunters were called in and more than 70 names considered before the job
came back on the market after Mr David Arculus, group managing director of
Emap the publishing company, turned it down. The headhunters are expected to
be paid about Pounds 100,000 for 'finding' Mr Quinn and a central scheduler.
</TEXT>
