<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JUL 92 / Slow US growth weighs on Bush
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT George Bush flew his faltering re-election campaign to Texas and
California yesterday, weighed down by the excess baggage of a US economy
that continues to disappoint.
He left Washington as the Commerce Department reported preliminary estimates
that gross domestic product in the second quarter of this year had expanded
at a real annual rate of only 1.4 per cent, less than half the revised 2.9
per cent increase of the first three months. Earlier estimates for first
quarter growth had been 2.7 per cent.
In Texas, the president conceded that 'the economy is not growing fast
enough' but he added, 'we should resist the urge to exaggerate our
problems.'
Senior administration officials hold to the prediction that growth would
average an annualised 3 per cent in the second half of the year. Mr Bush
insisted: 'We've got to act now to guarantee that."
But, in yet again blaming the Democrats in Congress for 'dillying and
dallying' over his economic recovery plan, he offered no new policy
solutions to an economic problem that is seriously undermining his electoral
chances.
It is providing the surging campaign of Mr Bill Clinton, the Democratic
presidential nominee, with ammunition and it is inducing some Republican
conservatives to start demanding that Mr Bush step down, rather than ditch
Vice-President Dan Quayle, as others have suggested.
In fact, on Wednesday night, the Senate Finance Committee agreed a Dollars
21.8bn tax bill containing some elements proposed by the president, among
them the creation of 25 urban enterprise zones, a 15 per cent tax allowance
on new investment undertaken over the next year and a Dollars 2,500 tax
credit for new home buyers.
Excluded, however, was a general capital gains tax cut which Mr Bush had
favoured.
Lex, page 16
</TEXT>
