<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JUL 92 / Dixons' Pounds 1m to aid study into ethics of business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR STANLEY Kalms, the elec-tronics dealer who turned a modest photo business
into the Dixons group of 1,500 shops, said yesterday the company was
donating Pounds 1m to the London Business School to promote the study of
business ethics.
That is small beer in comparison with the tens of millions spent by Dixons
in deadly contests waging and resisting hostile takeovers. But it might,
perhaps, help to make the takeover market a little more gentlemanly when it
begins again after the recession.
For Mr Kalms, who never attended university and began in his Polish-born
father's photo business at the age of 16, joint ventures with the likes of
London Business School are novel. But - no stranger to heated disputation -
he would have a distinctive contribution to make to the LBS seminar circuit.
The Dixons funding will be used to create a chair - one of the first of its
kind in the UK - and a 'major research and teaching programme' in business
ethics and social responsibility. The aim, says the LBS, is to create 'a
European flagship programme in the area'.
Its claims on that score will not go undisputed. Manchester Business School
believes it got there first, with its Co-op Bank chair of Corporate
Responsibility, set up last year and about to be filled.
The LBS stresses 'pressures' and 'processes' as the core of business ethics;
the words 'right' and 'wrong' do not appear to feature.
'Businesses have responsibilities to many different constituencies -
employees, customers, shareholders, local residents, the wider public and
the environment - creating conflicting pressures,' says Professor George
Bain, the dean at the LBS.
'It is vital that managers are made aware of how to manage the process of
reconciling those pressures.'
Dixons is no stranger to ethics controversies. In the late 1980s it was
caught up in a storm about the surveillance of former employees during a
hostile takeover bid. A private detective employed by the company was jailed
for bugging, unbeknown to Mr Kalms, the phones of former employees.
Explaining his donation, Mr Kalms said ethics training should be 'a part of
the ordinary process of skill development for managers'.
Maximising return for shareholders? 'You should still maximise it, but in a
framework of responsibility,' he responded.
If MBA students at the LBS will do their 'ethics management' between stints
on marketing and balance sheets, the Co-op and Manchester Business School
appear more at ease with the ancient verities.
Mr Terry Thomas, the Co-op Bank's managing director, explained the purpose
of their funding: 'The post-war years have seen the development of the mind
of the corporation: it's now overdue for the heart and soul of companies to
receive equivalent attention.'
Editorial Comment, Page 14
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-10231</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CG4BOAD8FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920731
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JUL 92 / ICI sets out radical plan to split its operations: Two units
envisaged to cover drugs and bulk chemicals operations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IMPERIAL Chemical Industries yesterday signalled the European chemicals
industry's most important shake-up since the second world war by proposing
to split itself into two separate companies.
Under the radical proposal, ICI, founded in 1926, would float off its drugs
and agrochemicals operations, to be known as ICI Bio, as a separate
publicly-listed company. The remaining bulk chemical business would be known
as ICI.
The company also said ICI Bio would plan to raise cash through a share issue
at the time of the demerger.
The surprise move was welcomed by analysts, although some said the company
still had to answer questions about the allocation of debt and tax
liabilities before the demerger's benefits could be evaluated. In spite of
poor half-year results announced yesterday, ICI's shares ended 76p up at
Pounds 11.71.
Sir Denys Henderson would be chairman of the two groups which would continue
to share the headquarters at Millbank in London for at least two years.
Mr Ronnie Hampel, presently chief operating officer, would be chief
executive of ICI. Mr David Barnes, presently a board member with
responsibility for the Americas and Europe, would become chief executive of
ICI Bio.
Shareholders would receive one share in each of the new companies for every
existing ICI share.
ICI, with a turnover of about Pounds 9bn, would drop from number five in the
world chemicals industry to number seven. The pharmaceuticals company, with
turnover of about Pounds 4bn, would become the world's ninth largest drugs
group.
The decision to draw up detailed plans to split the company was taken in
December last year, seven months after Lord Hanson surprised the City by
taking a 2.8 per cent stake in the chemicals giant, prompting speculation
that he might make a bid.
The proposal was put forward by Mr John Mayo of SG Warburg, ICI's financial
adviser. Mr Mayo, a 36-year-old corporate finance director at Warburg,
worked with a small team on the proposal for four months. It was
unofficially put to the board in April, and was finally approved in
principle on Wednesday.
A final decision on whether to demerge will not be taken until the
publication of the group's preliminary results in February 1993. Sir Denys
said the proposals would allow the separate groups to take part more fully
in the coming restructuring of the world's chemicals industry.
'For the businesses, the move would provide the chance to seize
opportunities for global expansion from a firm financial platform,' Sir
Denys said.
'Each of the new groupings would enable each company to respond better to
future opportunities.
'ICI now comprises two distinct families of businesses with the same values,
but very different technologies, operating requirements and market needs.'
Analysts argue that the separation would also make the two groups far less
vulnerable to takeover. ICI's Bio would be too expensive for a contested
takeover. The group's remaining operations would be unattractive as a
target.
Lord White, chairman of Hanson Industries, the conglomerate's North American
arm, and partner of Lord Hanson, said yesterday: 'If ICI had not spent so
much time during the last year fighting a bid that was never made and spent
it on seeing how it could improve shareholder value it might have come up
with a better solution a lot earlier.'
The plan would represent one of the largest restructurings of the European
chemicals industry since the Allies broke up I G Farben of Germany.
The plan envisages ICI consisting of its existing paints, materials,
industrial chemicals and explosives businesses. ICI Bio would have the
pharmaceuticals, agrochemicals, seeds and remaining specialty chemicals
operations.
THE BREAK-UP OF ICI
